<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,153,539]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
The diagnosis for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1919" box="[359,488,153,179]" genus="Homalictus" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[359,488,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Homalictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
remains unchanged, see 
<bibRefCitation author="Cockerell, T. D. A." box="[775,970,153,179]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="9 - 14" refId="ref25059" refString="Cockerell, T. D. A. (1919) The metallic-colored halictine bees of the Philippine Islands. Philippine Journal of Science, 15, 9 - 14. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 11763" type="journal article" year="1919">Cockerell (1919)</bibRefCitation>
. Here we summarise characters common to all Fijian 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1919" box="[291,420,189,215]" genus="Homalictus" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[291,420,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Homalictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(male and female). The Fijian 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1919" box="[774,903,189,215]" genus="Homalictus" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[774,903,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Homalictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have open to sparse (
<figureCitation box="[1152,1221,189,215]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1127,1152]" captionTargetBox="[200,1387,175,1093]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[200,1387,174,1108]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Grades of (a) pit density and (b) pit size. Reproduced from Houston (1975) with permission from CSIRO Publishing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3458340" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3458340/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), moderate to long hairs covering their heads and thoraces; some hairs on the dorsal side of the metasoma becoming denser posteriorly and long to very long hairs on the ventral surface of the metasoma, with the longest and densest hairs on females. All females possess a black fovea along the proximal anterior margin of the eyes; this feature was also found in some males and might indicate feminization in some species. Mandibles of both males and females can be simple or bidentate and vary within species, perhaps the result of wear. The propodeum has a weak carina along the posterior dorsal margin, this can be depressed medially, or not, and can vary in breadth. The number of spines on the inner hind tibial spur varies greatly with 4â€“18 spines found on 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Perkins &amp; Cheesman" baseAuthorityYear="1928" box="[793,915,441,467]" genus="Homalictus" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" rank="species" species="fijiensis">
<emphasis box="[793,915,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">H. fijiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
alone and a range of one or two for other species. The claws of all specimens examined were cleft. The redescriptions below for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Perkins &amp; Cheesman" baseAuthorityYear="1928" box="[1103,1225,477,503]" genus="Homalictus" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" rank="species" species="fijiensis">
<emphasis box="[1103,1225,477,503]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">H. fijiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Michener" authorityYear="1979" box="[1240,1394,477,503]" genus="Homalictus" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" rank="species" species="hadrander">
<emphasis box="[1240,1394,477,503]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">H. hadrander</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="Homalictus" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" rank="species" species="achrostus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">H. achrostus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Perkins &amp; Cheesman" baseAuthorityYear="1928" box="[320,466,513,539]" genus="Homalictus" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" rank="species" species="versifrons">
<emphasis box="[320,466,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">H. versifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are provided to standardise the descriptions of Fijian 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1919" box="[1068,1197,513,539]" genus="Homalictus" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1068,1197,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Homalictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
